The '''Tsuchimikado School''' (土御門流, Tsuchimikado-ryū) refers to a school of {{ill|Yūsoku Kojitsu|ja|有職故実}} (court practices and precedents) originating from the {{ill|Murakami Genji|ja|村上源氏}} Chūin branch, founded by {{ill|Minamoto no Morofusa|ja|源師房}}, also known as the "Tsuchimikado Udaijin" (土御門右大臣). This system was later formalized by Morofusa's grandsons, {{ill|Minamoto no Moroyori|ja|源師頼}} and {{ill|Minamoto no Morotoki|ja|源師時}}.== Overview ==Morofusa, a son of {{ill|Prince Tomohira|ja|具平親王}}, was orphaned at a young age and entered the {{ill|Minamoto no Makoto (court noble)|ja|藤原頼通}} household as a foster son. This upbringing allowed him to inherit the traditions of the {{ill|Kujō School|ja|九条流}} and {{ill|Midō School|ja|御堂流}} of the {{ill|Fujiwara Northern House|ja|藤原北家}}, alongside his unique contributions written in his diary, ''{{ill|Tsuchiu-ki|ja|土右記}}'', and his work, ''{{ill|Joi Jimyōshō|ja|叙位除目抄}}''. His knowledge was passed down to his son, {{ill|Minamoto no Toshifusa|ja|源俊房}}, and subsequently to Moroyori and Morotoki in the form of diaries, manuscripts, and oral traditions, with further enhancements and refinements.Although Morofusa’s lineage, represented by Toshifusa, suffered decline following the {{ill|Eikyū Disturbance|ja|永久の変}}, his younger brother, {{ill|Minamoto no Akifusa|ja|源顕房}}, continued the Chūin line, becoming the main inheritor of the Tsuchimikado traditions. Figures such as {{ill|Minamoto no Masazane|ja|源雅実}} upheld and advanced the practices, earning recognition for the school.The influence of the Tsuchimikado School extended beyond its family lineage. For example, {{ill|Fujiwara no Yorinaga|ja|藤原頼長}}, who referred to Moroyori as "Master" (先師) and himself as a "disciple" (弟子), extensively studied court practices and precedents under Moroyori, frequently consulting texts such as the ''Tsuchiu-ki'' for guidance.Additionally, {{ill|Minamoto no Arihito|ja|源有仁}}, a descendant of the {{ill|Later Sanjō Genji|ja|後三条源氏}}, who was maternally related to the Murakami Genji, studied the Tsuchimikado traditions and developed his own theories, later known as the {{ill|Hanazono School|ja|花園流}}. Despite the early extinction of Arihito’s lineage, the Hanazono School's theories and texts were inherited by the {{ill|Kanin School|ja|閑院流}}, contributing to the continuation and significance of both the Tsuchimikado and Hanazono traditions as prominent systems among non-regent families. These schools often engaged in debates with the Midō School, affiliated with the Fujiwara regent families, over ceremonial practices.== References ==* Hosoya, Kansuke. "Ceremonial Practices of the Heian Period and the Murakami Genji." First published in ''Chūsei Seiritsuki no Rekishizō'' (Tokyo-dō Shuppan, 1993, ISBN 978-4-490-20211-3). Republished as "The Rise of the Murakami Genji and the Formation of Ceremonial Practices" in ''Studies on the History of Medieval Court Ceremony Manuscripts'' (Bensei Publishing, 2007, ISBN 978-4-585-03158-1).== Related Articles ==* {{ill|Murakami Genji|ja|村上源氏}}]][[Category:Heian period]]]][[Category:Murakami Genji]]]][[Category:Unsorted completion categories]]
