The '''Tsuchimikado School''' (土御門流, Tsuchimikado-ryū) refers to a school of {{ill|Yūsoku Kojitsu|ja|有職故実|12=draft|12=draft}} (court practices and precedents) originating from the {{ill|Murakami Genji|ja|村上源氏|12=draft|12=draft}} Chūin branch, founded by {{ill|Minamoto no Morofusa|ja|源師房|12=draft|12=draft}}, also known as the "Tsuchimikado Udaijin" (土御門右大臣). This system was later formalized by Morofusa's grandsons, {{ill|Minamoto no Moroyori|ja|源師頼|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Minamoto no Morotoki|ja|源師時|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Overview ==
Morofusa, a son of {{ill|Prince Tomohira|ja|具平親王|12=draft|12=draft}}, was orphaned at a young age and entered the {{ill|Minamoto no Makoto (court noble)|ja|藤原頼通|12=draft|12=draft}} household as a foster son. This upbringing allowed him to inherit the traditions of the {{ill|Kujō School|ja|九条流|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Midō School|ja|御堂流|12=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Fujiwara Northern House|ja|藤原北家|12=draft|12=draft}}, alongside his unique contributions written in his diary, ''{{ill|Tsuchiu-ki|ja|土右記|12=draft|12=draft}}'', and his work, ''{{ill|Joi Jimyōshō|ja|叙位除目抄|12=draft|12=draft}}''. His knowledge was passed down to his son, {{ill|Minamoto no Toshifusa|ja|源俊房|12=draft|12=draft}}, and subsequently to Moroyori and Morotoki in the form of diaries, manuscripts, and oral traditions, with further enhancements and refinements.
Although Morofusa’s lineage, represented by Toshifusa, suffered decline following the {{ill|Eikyū Disturbance|ja|永久の変|12=draft|12=draft}}, his younger brother, {{ill|Minamoto no Akifusa|ja|源顕房|12=draft|12=draft}}, continued the Chūin line, becoming the main inheritor of the Tsuchimikado traditions. Figures such as {{ill|Minamoto no Masazane|ja|源雅実|12=draft|12=draft}} upheld and advanced the practices, earning recognition for the school.
The influence of the Tsuchimikado School extended beyond its family lineage. For example, {{ill|Fujiwara no Yorinaga|ja|藤原頼長|12=draft|12=draft}}, who referred to Moroyori as "Master" (先師) and himself as a "disciple" (弟子), extensively studied court practices and precedents under Moroyori, frequently consulting texts such as the ''Tsuchiu-ki'' for guidance.
Additionally, {{ill|Minamoto no Arihito|ja|源有仁|12=draft|12=draft}}, a descendant of the {{ill|Later Sanjō Genji|ja|後三条源氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, who was maternally related to the Murakami Genji, studied the Tsuchimikado traditions and developed his own theories, later known as the {{ill|Hanazono School|ja|花園流|12=draft|12=draft}}. Despite the early extinction of Arihito’s lineage, the Hanazono School's theories and texts were inherited by the {{ill|Kanin School|ja|閑院流|12=draft|12=draft}}, contributing to the continuation and significance of both the Tsuchimikado and Hanazono traditions as prominent systems among non-regent families. These schools often engaged in debates with the Midō School, affiliated with the Fujiwara regent families, over ceremonial practices.
== References ==
